    "summary": "Flax (Linum usitatissimum) was domesticated in the Fertile Crescent of the ancient Near East, with the earliest evidence for cultivation dating to approximately 7500–6500 BCE at sites in the northern Levant and southeastern Anatolia. Flax is a dual-purpose crop: its seeds yield linseed oil and are nutritious food, while its stem fibers can be processed into linen thread. The domestication of flax thus opened two distinct economic avenues simultaneously.\n\nLinen textiles woven from flax represent some of the earliest known fabric products in human history. The processing of flax fiber — which involves retting, breaking, and spinning — is labor-intensive but produces a strong, durable, and comfortable textile material. Flax cultivation and linen production spread rapidly across Europe and western Asia alongside other Neolithic agricultural practices, and linen remained one of the primary textile fibers of the ancient world from Egypt to Europe for thousands of years.",
